    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-20T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-20T13:00:00-05:00" n="699"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d699">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.20281/8: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Casablanca</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Goold</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Casablanca</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-20T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 20, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 21—8:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>207. Your 118, November 6, noon. All movements of vessels from Casablanca are
                    reported by the Admiralty to the German delegate who represents the Wiesbaden
                    Commission here. This was stated to me today by the Chief of Staff who evaded a
                    reply to my question whether Herr Klaube had ever interfered with any
                    departure.</p>
                <p>The German delegate lives and works at a hotel, seldom if ever visits the port,
                    and is unknown to the Director of Customs or the agent of the French Line. Herr
                    Klaube told Mayer<note n="93" xml:id="d699fn93">Ernest de Wael Mayer, Vice
                        Consul at Casablanca.</note> the other day that he had little to do and
                    hoped to move south in the near future. He has given up the project of taking a
                    house. He stated that he might be an advance agent for German consular
                    representatives here. He himself had formerly been Consul and Lufthansa
                    representative at Bathurst.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Tangier and Vichy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Goold</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
